REPORTS FROM BORDEAUX indicate clearly and indisputably that the 1961 Clarets, which have been declared exceptionally fine, have yielded less than 40% of a normal crop. And today, not long after the harvest, the ’61s are commanding a price, on the Bordeaux mar- ket, that is double what the °59s obtained two years ago!

This does not mean that the 1961 vintage is superior than 1959—we would be the first to question that any vintage can easily surpass 1959—but it simply reflects the world demand for great wines. We are offering a collection of 1959 Clarets on this page—we do admit that they are not inexpensive—but we must assert that the wines are truly great, in many instances, below the wholesale trade level that now prevails in Bordeaux—and they will surely command ‘considerably higher quotations a year from now.

OUR ADVICE IS SIMPLE—our prices will move upwards when this sale expires—if you want 1959 Clarets, buy them now or resign yourself to never having the personal pleasure of their fantastic greatness in your wine cellar.
